Replace O_NONBLOCK with select.select() in esc_detector() and read_key()

On macOS, stdin (fd 0), stdout (fd 1), and stderr (fd 2) share the same
kernel file description. Setting O_NONBLOCK on stdin via fcntl also makes
stdout non-blocking. When stdout is non-blocking and the output buffer is
full, write() raises BlockingIOError (errno 35 / EWOULDBLOCK).

This manifested during QR code login: the esc_detector daemon thread sets
O_NONBLOCK on stdin. After the thread exits, the main thread calls print()
on now-non-blocking stdout, causing the crash.

Using select.select() to poll for readable data on stdin avoids modifying
any fd flags entirely.

